    "divine_council_note": "This passage presents a critical divine council theology: judgment extends to rebellious council members, not just humanity. [B] The 'host of Azazel' (54:4) indicates that the arch-Watcher has subordinate spirits under his command—a corrupted hierarchy within the divine council. [A] This aligns with Deuteronomy 32:8-9, where YHWH assigns nations to b'nei 'elohim (sons of God), creating a tiered divine administration. When these administrators rebel (as in Psalm 82), they face demotion and judgment. [C] The Enochic tradition specifies that Azazel's rebellion was the paradigmatic case: he led 200 Watchers in the Genesis 6 descent, taught forbidden arts (1 Enoch 8:1), and corrupted the earth. The chains prepared for him are not metaphorical—they represent the complete removal of his authority and freedom. [B] The New Testament picks up this theology: principalities and powers (archai, exousiai) are real spiritual authorities that can be in rebellion (Ephesians 6:12, Colossians 2:15). Christ's victory includes disarming these rebellious powers. The valley of judgment in 1 Enoch 53-54 is where this disarmament becomes permanent imprisonment.",
    
